<Layout title="Substance Use & Withdrawal Assessment Tools" description="Substance use and withdrawal assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Substance Use &amp; Withdrawal</div>
  <h1>Substance Use &amp; Withdrawal Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Screening and monitoring tools for alcohol, opioid, benzodiazepine, and other substance use disorders.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>CAGE Questionnaire</strong> — Four-item alcohol dependency screening: Cut down, Annoyed, Guilty, Eye-opener. Score ≥2 indicates probable alcohol dependence.</li>
      <li><strong>AUDIT (Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test)</strong> — 10-item WHO tool for hazardous and harmful alcohol use. Score 8–15 simple advice; 16–19 brief counseling; ≥20 specialist referral.</li>
      <li><strong>AUDIT-C</strong> — Three-item abbreviated AUDIT assessing frequency, quantity, and binge drinking. Score ≥3 (women) or ≥4 (men) is positive for harmful drinking.</li>
      <li><strong>DAST-10 (Drug Abuse Screening Test)</strong> — 10-item self-report tool for drug use disorders excluding alcohol. Score 0 no problem; 1–2 low; 3–5 moderate; 6–8 substantial; 9–10 severe.</li>
      <li><strong>CIWA-Ar (Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Alcohol-Revised)</strong> — 10-item scale for alcohol withdrawal severity monitoring. Score ≥10 warrants pharmacotherapy; guides benzodiazepine dosing.</li>
      <li><strong>CIWA-B (Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment for Benzodiazepines)</strong> — Adapts CIWA framework for benzodiazepine withdrawal monitoring; guides tapering protocols.</li>
      <li><strong>COWS (Clinical Opiate Withdrawal Scale)</strong> — 11-item observational scale for opioid withdrawal severity. Guides buprenorphine induction timing; score ≥8–12 indicates sufficient withdrawal for induction.</li>
      <li><strong>CRAFFT Screening Tool</strong> — Adolescent substance use screening: Car, Relax, Alone, Forget, Friends, Trouble. Score ≥2 indicates high risk requiring further evaluation.</li>
      <li><strong>SBIRT Framework</strong> — Screening, Brief Intervention, and Referral to Treatment: evidence-based public health approach for identifying and addressing substance use across health care settings.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
